		<a name="83960"></a>
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;10/13/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 21:26:49</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=6008"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=6008')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=83960&amp;TOPIC_ID=9692&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Nerfs+are+Great+as+long+as+it+doesn%27t+happen+to+us&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>No, that's simply a preception, rather unintelligent and at its core whats wrong with EQ, class jealousy.</P><P>If what you said was true, than the game is much more fun for the warrior in a group if a Monk is sitting right next to you with the LFG tag on.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote><BR>You misunderstand what i mean.</P><P>Let me give an example, the monk nerf. A warrior is designed to tank, thats his main purpose in the game. A warrior gives up certain things, such as better damage output and more flexibility compaired to other melees, to do this.</P><P>If a monk who did not make these same sacrifices the warrior did can tank just as well as a warrior, or practically the same as a warrior, <b>no one wants a warrior</b>. Groups can just get monks who offer <i>more over all</i> than warriors or other real tanks do. </P><P>So you see, when monks get nerfed, its not the warrior enjoying gloating over the monks misery from the inside looking out, its quite the opposite. Whereas the WARRIOR was the one on the outside looking in, groups now have a reason to invite <b>both</b> the warrior and monk to fufill their perspective roles. </P><P>Thats just one example. Sometimes nerfs happen which whether intentionally or not, do not to make underpowered classes more desirable, but rather desirable classes undesirable. <BR>These nerfs are the ones that truely suck... although its still to early to tell but it looks like the mod rod nerf is going to be like that.</P><P>Anyway my point is you cant just say that "nerfs benefit no one", they arent that simple and one dimensional. Nerfs are complex and effect the game and classes on many different levels. Sometimes its true (when the nerf is entirely pve in nature it usually is mostly true), but USUALLY nerfs serve a purpose to primarily <b>help</b> player balance from a game standpoint.<BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>I guess Enchanters and Beastlords are now better because the Mage isn't casting mod rods?</P><P>Hmm, nope.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote><BR>Indirectly, yes they are.</P><P>In my groups pre nerf you really couldnt tell the difference between casters with kei, and casters without. Why? because mod rods were so powerful that the regen for my groups casters eclipsed it by nearly 3 times. I could have easily pushed that further, too.</P><P>KEI, ft, and any other form of mana regen was totally undermined by mod rods. Even though im a mage, i really cant deny that that is a fair state of affairs.</P><P>Im not saying the mod nerf is good. Its more bad than good since without mod rods mages are an incomplete class. But assuming they give us abilities to fill the void left by mod rods (but without overpowering us), I would even agree this was a fair and needed change.<BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>The Enchanter and the Beastlord function exactly the same, you still only need 1 to buff everybody. Perhaps Beastlords and Enchanters should have spent more time, not trying to get Mod Rods nerfed, and instead having their own classes improved?<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote><BR>Potus it comes down to an issue of whats easiest. Its easier to say/do "nerf monk ac" than it is to say/do<BR>"upgrade warrior ac avoidence factors and armor, and then upgrade all environments and mobs to account for the relative increase in player strength"</P><P> It really doesnt matter which way you do it (direct or indirect) because in the end, you achieve the desired effect and everyones abilities fall in line relative to each other and their environments. Relativity is all that matters in this game, the numbers are irrelivant.</P><P><BR> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
